Determinants of Loan Application, Repayment and Profitability¶

by Durowoju Oluwadamilola¶

Investigation Overview¶

In this investigation, I look at factors that influences loan application, repayment and profitability(as an investor). My focus is investigating the relationship between listing categories, incomerange, stated monthly income, loan term, prosper rating on the loan status categories.

Dataset Overview¶

Prosper is a peer-to-peer lending marketplace that helps in facilitating loans. This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. This Sheet contains information about the dataset variables. Some columns were renamed, assigned the correct datatype, ordered accordingly to assist the analysis.

Distribution of Loan Status¶

Loan status is a categorical variable with large values with the least being 5 and 56576 at highest. Therefore,I plotted using the logarithmic scale on the y-axis. Most of the loans are in current status followed by the Completed status according to their count. There is a high number of chargedoff loans which is a loss for the investor.

Determinants of Loan Application¶

Distribution of Borrowers Income Range¶

IncomeRange is an ordinal categorical variable. Most borrowers fall within the income range of $25000-$74999 even though not all income groups were properly represented. From the result, I say that the middle class are more prone to borrowing. I used a logarithmic scale because of the large data ranges.

Distribution of Listing Categories¶

This is to investigate reason for loan acquistion amongst other factors. Most loans are acquired to consolidate debts followed by unexplainable reasons(NA & Other). Other reasons include home improvement and business purpose.

Determinants of Loan Repayment¶

Borrower Interest Rate across Loan Terms¶

BorrowerRate and BorrowerAPR can be determinants of either completed or default loans over loan terms. For both 36 and 60 months term, their shape of distribution of BorrowerRate and BorrowerAPR is quite similar. I see that the difference in median values of borrowerRate and BorrowerAPR for these terms is minimal compared to the 12 months loan term. This implies that short term loans (12months) have higher interest rates compared to mid or long term loans.

Determinant of Loan Profitability¶

Estimated Yield and Return of Loans by Term¶

For EstimatedEffectiveYield, loans with 60 months term tend to have an high yield of 0.1%-0.2% while it is lower for EstimatedReturn (<0.1%), due to the EstimatedLoss Rate being subtracted. For both 12 and 36 months term, the difference between EstimatedEffectiveYield and EstimatedReturn is quite high based on shape of the distribution of the boxplots. It turns out that long term loans(60months) tends to more profitable for an investor.

Risk and return expressed by Prosper rating¶

Since ProsperRatings were used for loans after July 2009. Therefore, this analysis will be aimed at the loan dataset after July 2009. According to Prosper, 'AA' represents loans with lower risk and lower return while 'HR' represents loans with higher risk and higher return. From the plot, 12 and 60 months Term produced positive estimated returns while 36 months has negative estimated returns for some ratings. Indeed, 'HR' rating implies higher returns but the 'E' has a wider return margin compared to 'HR'. I assume loans with 'E' rating might surpass 'HR' rating in terms of estimated return for any loan term.
